      "source": [
        "### Loading an image using OpenCV\n",
        "\n",
        "We can read the image using imread module.\n",
        "* It takes 2 arguments:\n",
        "1. **path:** A string representing the path of the image to be read.\n",
        "2. **flag:** It specifies the way in which image should be read. It’s default value is cv2.IMREAD_COLOR\n",
        "\n",
        "Describing the 3 possible values of flag below:\n",
        "* **cv2.IMREAD_COLOR:** It specifies to load a color image. Any transparency of image will be neglected. It is the default flag. Alternatively, we can pass integer value 1 for this flag.\n",
        "* **cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE:** It specifies to load an image in grayscale mode. Alternatively, we can pass integer value 0 for this flag.\n",
        "* **cv2.IMREAD_UNCHANGED:** It specifies to load an image as such including alpha channel. Alternatively, we can pass integer value -1 for this flag.\n",
        "\n",
        "In short:\n",
        "* The 1 in the flag parameter denotes that it is a color image.\n",
        "* If the parameter is 0, it would mean that the image being imported is a grayscale image.\n",
        "\n",
        "Since the image I'm using is coloured, I'll use 1.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 2,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "7EFw_aj300sg"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [

        "By shape of the image, we mean the shape of the NumPy array. As you see from executing the code, the matrix consists of 530 rows and 1136 columns.\n",
        "\n",
        "The last value 3 indicates the no. of channels.\n",
        "\n",
        "3 = coloured image\n",
        "1 = black and white/grayscale image"

      "source": [
        "## Displaying the image\n",
        "Displaying an image using OpenCV is pretty simple and straightforward. Consider the below image:\n",
        "\n",
        "**Note:** The imshow method of cv2 is disabled in Google Colab. Thus, colab users need to import cv2_imshow for displaying images.\n",
        "\n",
        "So the commands will be like:\n",
        "* Jupyter Notebook: cv2.imshow()\n",
        "* Google Colab: cv2_imshow()\n",
        "\n",
        "Now, just displaying the image often leads to crashing.\n",
        "\n",
        "**The Problem**\n",
        "The Notebook it is not usually happy to accommodate the window created by imshow. So it just crashes the window.\n",
        "\n",
        "**The Solution**\n",
        "To solve this, you need to explicitly close the window when you are done with it. To accomplish this, you can use the cv2.destroyAllWindows() functionality.\n",
        "\n",
        "Since you probably don’t want your screen to close immediately, you can tell OpenCV to wait for a keypress.\n",
        "\n",
        "* waitKey(0) will display the window infinitely until any keypress (it is suitable for image display).\n",
        "\n",
        "* waitKey(1) will display a frame for 1 ms, after which display will be automatically closed. If you specify 25 inside the brackets, it will display for 25ms.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 242
        },
        "id": "yocWaX1W136P",
        "outputId": "f55802c3-7a08-4da9-bb11-68ef79cc17e3"
      },
      "outputs": [

          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<PIL.Image.Image image mode=RGB size=224x225>"
            ],
            "image/png": "\n",
            "image/jpeg": "\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# For Colab users\n",
        "from google.colab.patches import cv2_imshow\n",
        "cv2_imshow(img)\n",
        "\n",
        "# For Jupyter Notebook users:\n",
        "# cv2.imshow(“Penguin”, img)  # Here, \"Penguin\" is the name that'll be given to the window\n",
        "\n",
        "# waiting for key event\n",
        "cv2.waitKey(0)\n",
        "\n",
        "# destroying all windows\n",
        "cv2.destroyAllWindows()"
      ]
    },

      "source": [
        "### Converting to Grayscale\n",
        "\n",
        "cvtColor() function in OpenCV is very helpful in converting color channels from one to another such as BRG to HSV or BRG to RGB. The same method can be used to convert BRG to GRAY by using the cv2.cvtColor(img,cv2.BGR2GRAY)\n",
        "\n",
        "Another method is to specify 0 instead of 1 as the flag parameter in imread(). That way, your image will be read as a grayscale image."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 242
        },
        "id": "eFYwDl9I5ZHU",
        "outputId": "522c674b-d7c0-4816-b5b9-ed34b6c366a7"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<PIL.Image.Image image mode=L size=224x225>"
            ],
            "image/png": "\n",
            "image/jpeg": "\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# Converting color image to grayscale image\n",
        "gray_img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Showing the converted image\n",
        "\n",
        "# Colab users:\n",
        "cv2_imshow(gray_img)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Jupyter Notebook users:\n",
        "# cv2_imshow(\"Converted Image\",gray_img)\n",
        "\n",
        "# waiting for key event\n",
        "cv2.waitKey(0)\n",
        "\n",
        "# destroying all windows\n",
        "cv2.destroyAllWindows()"
      ]
    },

        "\n"
      ]
    },

        "image_rgb = cv2.cvtColor(img1, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)\n",
        "cv2_imshow(img1)\n",

        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "X = cv2.imread(\"mandril.png\",0)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",

      ],
      "source": [
        "d = 5   # sampling each d pixels\n",
        "(Nx,Mx) = X.shape\n",
        "ix = range(0,Nx,d)\n",
        "jx = range(0,Mx,d)\n",
        "Ny = len(ix)\n",
        "My = len(jx)\n",
        "Y = np.zeros((Ny,My),np.uint8)\n",
        "for i in range(Ny):\n",
        "  for j in range(My):\n",
        "    Y[i,j] = X[ix[i],jx[j]]\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))\n",
        "plt.imshow(Y,cmap='gray')\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
      ]

        "o=np.zeros((row-fr-1,col-fc-1))\n",
        "o1=np.zeros((row-fr-1,col-fc-1))"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "63RKoNqPQ6ut"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "for i in range(0, row-fr-1):\n",
        "   for j in range (0,col-fc-1):\n",
        "    o[i,j]=sum(sum(np.multiply(x[i:i+fr,j:j+fc],f)))\n",
        "    o1[i,j]=sum(sum(np.multiply(x[i:i+fr,j:j+fc],f1)))\n",
        "    o2[i,j]=sum(sum(np.multiply(x[i:i+fr,j:j+fc],f2)))\n",
        "    o3[i,j]=sum(sum(np.multiply(x[i:i+fr,j:j+fc],f3)))"
      ],
      "metadata": {
